             sworn.</p>
               <p>Deposed, he had lost a quarter of malt in two sacks, out of his barge, that he had a suspicion they were on board a barge close to his; on the 24th following I saw Mr. Church, the master of the barge, and they searched and found it there, and when they found it, the prisoner at the bar, said the malt was his, he bought it; the malt was shot out of the sacks and put in their own, I did not find my sacks.</p>
               <p>Court. Can you undertake to swear to the malt, when in other sacks? - Yes; it is pale malt, a particular malt.</p>
               <p>Is not there other pale malt as well as your's? - Yes; but it has a particular flavour.</p>
               <p>Is there any other evidence? - No.</p>
               <p>Mr. Recorder. I think it utterly impossible to swear to it, after it was out of your sacks.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t17811205-54-verdict290" type="verdictDescription">
